# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ebpf
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] The **Berkeley Packet Filter** (**BPF**; also **BSD Packet Filter**, **classic BPF** or **cBPF**) is a network tap mechanism and packet filter which permits computer network packets to be captured and filtered at the operating system level.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] It provides a raw interface to data link layers, permitting raw link-layer packets to be sent and received, and allows a userspace process to supply a filter program that specifies which packets it wants to receive.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] For example, a tcpdump process may want to receive only packets that initiate a TCP connection.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF returns only packets that pass the filter that the process supplies.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] This avoids copying unwanted packets from the operating system kernel to the process, greatly improving performance.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] The filter program is in the form of instructions for a virtual machine, which are interpreted, or compiled into machine code by a just-in-time (JIT) mechanism and executed, in the kernel.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is used by programs that need to, among other things, analyze network traffic.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] If the driver for the network interface supports promiscuous mode, it allows the interface to be put into that mode so that all packets on the network can be received, even those destined to other hosts.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] The BPF filtering mechanism is available on most Unix-like operating systems.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is sometimes used to refer to just the filtering mechanism, rather than to the entire interface.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Some systems, such as Linux and Tru64 UNIX, provide a raw interface to the data link layer other than the BPF raw interface but use the BPF filtering mechanisms for that raw interface.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] The Linux kernel provides an extended version of the BPF filtering mechanism, called eBPF, which uses a JIT mechanism, and which is used for packet filtering, as well as for other purposes in the kernel. eBPF is also available for Microsoft Windows.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] The original paper was written by Steven McCanne and Van Jacobson in 1992 while at Lawrence Berkeley Laboratory.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF provides pseudo-devices that can be bound to a network interface; reads from the device will read buffers full of packets received on the network interface, and writes to the device will inject packets on the network interface.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] While one copy remains in the receipt path for user processes, this preserves the independence of different BPF device consumers, as well as allowing the packing of headers into the BPF buffer rather than copying complete packet data.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF's filtering capabilities are implemented as an interpreter for a machine language for the BPF virtual machine, a 32-bit machine with fixed-length instructions, one accumulator, and one index register.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Programs in that language can fetch data from the packet, perform arithmetic operations on data from the packet, and compare the results against constants or against data in the packet or test bits in the results, accepting or rejecting the packet based on the results of those tests.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] BPF is often extended by "overloading" the load (ld) and store (str) instructions.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Traditional Unix-like BPF implementations can be used in userspace, despite being written for kernel-space.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] This is accomplished using preprocessor conditions.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Since version 3.18, the Linux kernel includes an extended BPF virtual machine with ten 64-bit registers, termed eBPF.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] It can be used for non-networking purposes, such as for attaching eBPF programs to various tracepoints.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Since kernel version 3.19, eBPF filters can be attached to sockets, and, since kernel version 4.1, to traffic control classifiers for the ingress and egress networking data path.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] The original and obsolete version has been retroactively renamed to *classic BPF* (*cBPF*).
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Nowadays, the Linux kernel runs eBPF only and loaded cBPF bytecode is transparently translated into an eBPF representation in the kernel before program execution.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] All bytecode is verified before running to prevent denial-of-service attacks.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Until Linux 5.3, the verifier prohibited the use of loops, to prevent potentially unbounded execution times; loops with bounded execution time are now permitted in more recent kernels.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Some projects use BPF instruction sets or execution techniques different from the originals.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Some platforms, including FreeBSD, NetBSD, and WinPcap, use a just-in-time compiler (JIT) to convert BPF instructions into native code in order to improve performance.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Linux includes a BPF JIT compiler which is disabled by default.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Kernel-mode interpreters for that same virtual machine language are used in raw data link layer mechanisms in other operating systems, such as Tru64 Unix, and for socket filters in the Linux kernel and in the WinPcap and Npcap packet capture mechanism.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] That interpreter can also be used when reading a file containing packets captured using pcap.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Another user-mode interpreter is *uBPF*, which supports JIT and eBPF (without cBPF).
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Its code has been reused to provide eBPF support in non-Linux systems.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Microsoft's *eBPF on Windows* builds on uBPF and the PREVAIL formal verifier.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] *rBPF*, a Rust rewrite of uBPF, is used by the Solana blockchain platform as the execution engine.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF is generally emitted by a program from some very high-level textual rule describing the pattern to match.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] One such representation is found in libpcap.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Classic BPF and eBPF can also be written either directly as machine code, or using an assembly language for a textual representation.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Notable assemblers include Linux kernel's `bpf_asm` tool (cBPF), `bpfc` (cBPF), and the `ubpf` assembler (eBPF).
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] The `bpftool` command can also act as a disassembler for both flavors of BPF.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] The assembly languages are not necessarily compatible with each other.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] eBPF bytecode has recently become a target of higher-level languages.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] LLVM added eBPF support in 2014, and GCC followed in 2019.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Both toolkits allow compiling C and other supported languages to eBPF.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] A subset of P4 can also be compiled into eBPF using BCC, an LLVM-based compiler kit.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] The Spectre attack could leverage the Linux kernel's eBPF interpreter or JIT compiler to extract data from other kernel processes.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] A JIT hardening feature in the kernel mitigates this vulnerability.
[src:ebpf/berkeley-packet-filter] Chinese computer security group Pangu Lab said the NSA used BPF to conceal network communications as part of a complex Linux backdoor.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] It is used to safely and efficiently extend the capabilities of the kernel at runtime without requiring changes to kernel source code or loading kernel modules.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Safety is provided through an in-kernel verifier which performs static code analysis and rejects programs which crash, hang or otherwise interfere with the kernel negatively.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] This validation model differs from sandboxed environments, where the execution environment is restricted and the runtime has no insight about the program.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Examples of programs that are automatically rejected are programs without strong exit guarantees (i.e. for/while loops without exit conditions) and programs dereferencing pointers without safety checks.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Loaded programs which passed the verifier are either interpreted or in-kernel just-in-time compiled (JIT compiled) for native execution performance.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Given eBPF's efficiency and flexibility opened up new possibilities to solve production issues, Brendan Gregg famously dubbed eBPF "superpowers for Linux".
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Linus Torvalds said, "BPF has actually been really useful, and the real power of it is how it allows people to do specialized code that isn't enabled until asked for".
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Due to its success in Linux, the eBPF runtime has been ported to other operating systems such as Windows.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] eBPF evolved from the classic Berkeley Packet Filter (cBPF, a retroactively-applied name).
[src:ebpf/ebpf] At the most basic level, it introduced the use of ten 64-bit registers (instead of two 32-bit long registers for cBPF), different jump semantics, a call instruction and corresponding register passing convention, new instructions, and a different encoding for these instructions.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Map implementations are provided by the core kernel.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] There are various types, including hash maps, arrays, and ring buffers.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The eBPF virtual machine runs within the kernel and takes in a program in the form of eBPF bytecode instructions which are converted to native machine instructions that run on the CPU.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Early implementations of eBPF saw eBPF bytecode interpreted, but this has now been replaced with a Just-in-Time (JIT) compilation process for performance and security-related reasons.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The eBPF virtual machine consists of eleven 64-bit registers with 32-bit subregisters, a program counter and a 512-byte large BPF stack space.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] These general purpose registers keep track of state when eBPF programs are executed.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Tail calls can call and execute another eBPF program and replace the execution context, similar to how the execve() system call operates for regular processes.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] This basically allows an eBPF program to call another eBPF program.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Tail calls are implemented as a long jump, reusing the same stack frame.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Tail calls are particularly useful in eBPF, where the stack is limited to 512 bytes.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] During runtime, functionality can be added or replaced atomically, thus altering the BPF program’s execution behavior.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] A popular use case for tail calls is to spread the complexity of eBPF programs over several programs.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Another use case is for replacing or extending logic by replacing the contents of the program array while it is in use.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] For example, to update a program version without downtime or to enable/disable logic.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] It is generally considered good practice in software development to group common code into a function, encapsulating logic for reusability.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Prior to Linux kernel 4.16 and LLVM 6.0, a typical eBPF C program had to explicitly direct the compiler to inline a function, resulting in a BPF object file that had duplicate functions.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] This restriction was lifted, and mainstream eBPF compilers now support writing functions naturally in eBPF programs.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] This reduces the generated eBPF code size, making it friendlier to a CPU instruction cache.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The verifier is a core component of eBPF, and its main responsibility is to ensure that an eBPF program is safe to execute.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] It performs a static analysis of the eBPF bytecode to guarantee its safety.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The verifier analyzes the program to assess all possible execution paths.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] It steps through the instructions in order and evaluates them.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The verification process starts with a depth-first search through all possible paths of the program, the verifier simulates the execution of each instruction using abstract interpretation, tracking the state of registers and stack if any instruction could lead to an unsafe state, verification fails.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] This process continues until all paths have been analyzed or a violation is found.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Depending on the type of program, the verifier checks for violations of specific rules.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] This is not an exhaustive list of the checks the verifier does, and there are exceptions to these rules.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] An example is that tracing programs have access to helpers that allow them to read memory in a controlled way, but these program types require root privileges and thus do not pose a security risk.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Over time the eBPF verifier has evolved to include newer features and optimizations, such as support for bounded loops, dead-code elimination, function-by-function verification, and callbacks.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] eBPF programs use the memory and data structures from the kernel.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Some structures can be modified between different kernel versions, altering the memory layout.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Since the Linux kernel is continuously developed, there is no guarantee that the internal data structures will remain the same across different versions.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] CO-RE is a fundamental concept in modern eBPF development that allows eBPF programs to be portable across different kernel versions and configurations.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] It addresses the challenge of kernel structure variations between different Linux distributions and versions.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] CO-RE comprises BTF (BPF Type Format) - a metadata format that describes the types used in the kernel and eBPF programs and provides detailed information about struct layouts, field offsets, and data types.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] It enables runtime accessibility of kernel types, which is crucial for BPF program development and verification.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] BTF is included in the kernel image of BTF-enabled kernels.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Special relocations are emitted by the compiler (e.g., LLVM).
[src:ebpf/ebpf] These relocations capture high-level descriptions of what information the eBPF program intends to access.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The libbpf library adapts eBPF programs to work with the data structure layout on the target kernel where they run, even if this layout is different from the kernel where the code was compiled.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] To do this, libbpf needs the BPF CO-RE relocation information generated by Clang as part of the compilation process.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The compiled eBPF program is stored in an Executable and Linkable Format (ELF) object file.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] This file contains BTF-type information and Clang-generated relocations.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The ELF format allows the eBPF loader (e.g., libbpf) to process and adjust the BPF program dynamically for the target kernel.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] At the first eBPF Summit there was a vote taken and the bee mascot was named "eBee".
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The logo was originally created by Vadim Shchekoldin.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Earlier unofficial eBPF mascots have existed in the past, but have not seen widespread adoption.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The eBPF Foundation was created in August 2021 with the goal to expand the contributions being made to extend the powerful capabilities of eBPF and grow beyond Linux.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Founding members include Meta, Google, Isovalent, Microsoft and Netflix.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] The purpose is to raise, budget, and spend funds in support of various open source, open data and/or open standards projects relating to eBPF technologies to further drive the growth and adoption of the eBPF ecosystem.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Since inception, Red Hat, Huawei, Crowdstrike, Tigera, DaoCloud, Datoms, FutureWei also joined.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Due to the ease of programmability, eBPF has been used as a tool for implementing microarchitectural timing side-channel attacks such as Spectre against vulnerable microprocessors.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] While unprivileged eBPF implements mitigations against Spectre v1, v2, and v4 for x86-64, unprivileged use has ultimately been disabled by the kernel community by default to protect users of unsupported architectures and limit the impact of future hardware vulnerabilities.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] On x86-64, Spectre v1 is mitigated through a combination of branchless bounds-enforcement (e.g., masking instructions) and the verification of speculative execution paths.
[src:ebpf/ebpf] Spectre v4 is mitigated exclusively through speculation barriers (i.e., lfence) and Spectre v2 is mitigated through retpoline when available or speculation barriers.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] The idea behind XDP is to add an early hook in the RX path of the kernel, and let a user supplied eBPF program decide the fate of the packet.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] The hook is placed in the network interface controller (NIC) driver just after the interrupt processing, and before any memory allocation needed by the network stack itself, because memory allocation can be an expensive operation.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] Due to this design, XDP can drop 26 million packets per second per core with commodity hardware.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] The eBPF program must pass a preverifier test before being loaded, to avoid executing malicious code in kernel space.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] The preverifier checks that the program contains no out-of-bounds accesses, loops or global variables.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] XDP requires support in the NIC driver but, as not all drivers support it, it can fallback to a generic implementation, which performs the eBPF processing in the network stack, though with slower performance.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] XDP has infrastructure to offload the eBPF program to a network interface controller which supports it, reducing the CPU load.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] In 2023, only Netronome cards support it.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] Microsoft is partnering with other companies and adding support for XDP in its MsQuic implementation of the QUIC protocol.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] Along with XDP, a new address family entered in the Linux kernel starting 4.18.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] AF_XDP, formerly known as AF_PACKETv4 (which was never included in the mainline kernel), is a raw socket optimized for high performance packet processing and allows zero-copy between kernel and applications.
[src:ebpf/express-data-path] As the socket can be used for both receiving and transmitting, it supports high performance network applications purely in user space.
